Date and Time

1) What are the main classes in the java.time package?
-->Answer:

The java.time package (introduced in Java 8) provides modern, immutable, and thread-safe classes for handling dates and times.

Common Classes :
| Class               | Purpose                                   |
| ------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| `LocalDate`         | Stores date only (yyyy-MM-dd)             |
| `LocalTime`         | Stores time only (HH:mm:ss)               |
| `LocalDateTime`     | Stores both date and time                 |
| `ZonedDateTime`     | Date and time with time zone              |
| `Instant`           | Represents a timestamp                    |
| `Duration`          | Time difference (hours, minutes, seconds) |
| `Period`            | Date difference (years, months, days)     |
| `DateTimeFormatter` | Formats and parses dates                  |

Example :
    import java.time.*;
    
    public class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
    
            System.out.println(LocalDate.now());
            System.out.println(LocalTime.now());
            System.out.println(LocalDateTime.now());
            System.out.println(ZonedDateTime.now());
        }
    }

Output (Example) :
    2026-07-24
    14:30:15
    2026-07-24T14:30:15
    2026-07-24T14:30:15+05:30[Asia/Kolkata]





2) How do you format a Date object in Java?
-->Answer:
There are two ways.

(A) Using SimpleDateFormat (Legacy)
          import java.util.Date;
          import java.text.SimpleDateFormat;
          
          public class Main {
              public static void main(String[] args) {
          
                  Date date = new Date();
          
                  SimpleDateFormat sdf =
                          new SimpleDateFormat("dd-MM-yyyy");
          
                  System.out.println(sdf.format(date));
              }
          }
          
          Output :
              24-07-2026
(B) Using DateTimeFormatter (Java 8+)
        import java.time.LocalDate;
        import java.time.format.DateTimeFormatter;
        
        public class Main {
        
            public static void main(String[] args) {
        
                LocalDate date = LocalDate.now();
        
                DateTimeFormatter formatter =
                        DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("dd-MM-yyyy");
        
                System.out.println(date.format(formatter));
            }
        }
        
        Output :
            24-07-2026

Interview Tip: Use DateTimeFormatter for Java 8+ because it is thread-safe.





3) How do you parse a string into a date?
-->Answer:

Use the parse() method.

Example
import java.time.LocalDate;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        LocalDate date =
                LocalDate.parse("2026-07-24");

        System.out.println(date);
    }
}

Output

2026-07-24
Parsing Custom Format
import java.time.LocalDate;
import java.time.format.DateTimeFormatter;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String s = "24-07-2026";

        DateTimeFormatter formatter =
                DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("dd-MM-yyyy");

        LocalDate date =
                LocalDate.parse(s, formatter);

        System.out.println(date);
    }
}

Output

2026-07-24





4) How to format LocalDate, LocalTime, LocalDateTime, and ZonedDateTime?
-->Answer:

Use the DateTimeFormatter class.

Example
import java.time.*;
import java.time.format.DateTimeFormatter;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        DateTimeFormatter formatter =
                DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("dd-MM-yyyy HH:mm:ss");

        System.out.println(LocalDate.now());

        System.out.println(LocalTime.now().format(DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("HH:mm:ss")));

        System.out.println(LocalDateTime.now().format(formatter));

        System.out.println(ZonedDateTime.now().format(formatter));
    }
}

Sample Output

2026-07-24
14:35:21
24-07-2026 14:35:21
24-07-2026 14:35:21





5) What are common format patterns (dd, MM, yyyy, HH, mm, ss, a)?
-->
| Pattern | Meaning         | Example |
| ------- | --------------- | ------- |
| `dd`    | Day             | 24      |
| `MM`    | Month           | 07      |
| `yyyy`  | Four-digit year | 2026    |
| `yy`    | Two-digit year  | 26      |
| `HH`    | Hour (24-hour)  | 14      |
| `hh`    | Hour (12-hour)  | 02      |
| `mm`    | Minutes         | 35      |
| `ss`    | Seconds         | 21      |
| `a`     | AM/PM           | PM      |
| `MMM`   | Short month     | Jul     |
| `MMMM`  | Full month      | July    |
| `E`     | Day name        | Fri     |

Example :
    DateTimeFormatter formatter =
            DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(
                    "dd/MM/yyyy HH:mm:ss a");
    
    System.out.println(
            LocalDateTime.now().format(formatter));

Output :
    24/07/2026 02:35:21 PM





6) Why is SimpleDateFormat not thread-safe?
-->Answer:

SimpleDateFormat is not thread-safe because it maintains internal mutable state while formatting and parsing dates.

If multiple threads use the same SimpleDateFormat object simultaneously, it may produce incorrect results or exceptions.

Unsafe Example :
      SimpleDateFormat sdf = new SimpleDateFormat("dd-MM-yyyy");
      
      If many threads use the same sdf, unexpected results may occur.

Solution :
      Create a separate SimpleDateFormat object for each thread, or
      Use DateTimeFormatter (Java 8+), which is immutable and thread-safe.




Interview Answer (One Line) :
-->SimpleDateFormat is not thread-safe because it uses mutable internal state. DateTimeFormatter is thread-safe
    because it is immutable.
